Privilege Escalation


Running the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the interesting entry above. Is it a password?


And bingo! It is Andre's password! Using this password UQfsdCB7aAP6, I successfully switched user to andre.


There is an interesting cronjob that is executed as root. By the looks of it, everything in the backup directory gets saved in a ZIP format at /tmp directory.


The note.txt contains the message above.


The binary tar can be used for PE. I created a bash shell with SUID bit set inside /tmp.Then I created the files that are similar to the tar options.


And the evil bash has been created with SUID bit set! Spawning a root shell was possible by entering /tmp/bash -p. GG.
